habitat_description:
In The United States, this frog only enters the territory in the Lower Rio Grande Valley in Texas, from there its distribution expands through Mexico as far south as Venezuela (Behler and King 1979; Conant and Collins 1998). 
Occupies a wide variety of habitats such as roadside ditches, damp meadows, drainages, and even irrigated fields (Conant and Collins 1998).
Breeding habitat consists of incubating chambers dug by males usually under logs, debris, or clay soils (Dixon and Heyer 1968). Males call from these chambers, but also observed calling from dirt clods. Clumps of grass, and small depressions (Garrett and Barker 1987). The habitat of the adults is characterized by abundant moisture and include irrigated agricultural ditches, low grasslands, runoff areas, semi-permanent waters, prairie potholes, resacas, and oxbow lakes (Lannoo 2005)
